{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586127"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:26:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:26:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15062"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15062"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.83,0.04,0.09,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67758"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7750"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15062"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53223"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18924"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67758"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlomerulonephritis comprises inflammatory conditions affecting the glomeruli. It can be classified into three main groups based on the primary pathological mechanism:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDamage to the glomerular permeability barrier leading to proteinuria (nephrotic syndrome)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESevere necrotising glomerular injury causing haematuria and rapid reduction in glomerular filtration rate (nephritic syndrome)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGlomerular inflammation with mesangial or subendothelial immune deposits\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a condition characterised by severe necrotising glomerular injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis","Minimal change disease","Membranous nephropathy","Lupus nephritis","IgA nephropathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapidly progressive glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by aggressive glomerular inflammation with crescent formation, leading to severe necrotising injury. This results in haematuria and rapid decline in glomerular filtration rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMinimal change disease\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects podocytes causing nephrotic syndrome with selective proteinuria\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMembranous nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E involves subepithelial immune deposits and presents with nephrotic syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELupus nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by immune complex deposition in various patterns\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E features mesangial IgA immune deposits\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these distinct pathological patterns helps guide appropriate diagnosis and management of glomerular diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis is characterised by severe necrotising glomerular injury with crescent formation leading to rapid decline in renal function","Nephrotic syndrome conditions (minimal change disease, membranous nephropathy) primarily affect the glomerular filtration barrier causing proteinuria","Immune complex glomerulonephritis (lupus nephritis, IgA nephropathy) is characterised by immune deposit formation"],"references":["Rout P, Naik RH, Leslie SW. Rapidly Progressive Glomerulonephritis. 2024 Jun 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491362.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53223"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15062"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53223"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T22:17:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T22:19:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7750"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67758"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.em